sentence: The S&P 500, Dow Jones Industrial Average, and the Nasdaq Composite eked out further gains on Monday to once again finish the day at record highs.
Reports suggesting that China is once again skeptical over a broad trade with the US were offset by the expected news the US will allow a 90-day extension for companies working with Huawei.

In other trade news, Japan's lower house of parliament approved a limited trade deal Prime Minister Shinzo Abe agreed with the US, paving the way for tariff cuts next year on items including US farm goods and Japanese machine tools.
Asia markets ended Tuesday trading on a higher note amid chatter the People’s Bank of China could lower its loan prime rate on Wednesday.
European markets are higher across the board following stronger than expected economic data out of Italy and data showing the region’s car sales jumped in October.
Absent fresh signs on progress on US-China trade talks, today's US stock market will be influenced by retail earnings.

As we get ready for the US market to open, US equity futures still point to a positive market open, however, disappointing retail earnings out this morning from Home Depot (HD) and Kohl’s (KSS) have walked back those futures from their morning highs.
Italy's industrial sales rose 0.2% month over month in September 2019, coming in stronger than the expected 0.4% fall.
Year-on-year, industrial sales slumped 1.6% in September better than the 2.2% drop recorded in August, but below the consensus forecast of -1%.
September Industrial Order in Italy posted a sharp rebound to an index level of 108.9 vs. 67.2 in August.
On a year over year basis, September orders rose 0.3%, head, and shoulders ahead of the expected 3.9% drop.
Today we will get some decent leading economic indicators for the domestic economy in the form of October Housing Starts and Building Permits.

We will also get the weekly Johnson Redbook Index which measures the growth in the U.S. retail sales and is based on the sales data of around 9,000 large general merchandise retailers representing over 80% of the equivalent 'official' retail sales series collected and published by the US Department of Commerce.

As a side note on the economic data front, the Citi Economic Surprise Index for the US which tracks how economic data comes in versus expectations moved back into negative territory late last week after 49 trading days in positive territory.

Shares of Home Depot (HD) are off in pre-market trading following the company's latest quarterly EPS results of $2.53 that matched expectations but revenue for the quarter came in $290 million lighter than expected.
Comparable same-store sales for the quarter rose 3.6%, well below the expected 4.6%.
In its guidance, Home Depot dialed back its revenue and comp sales growth forecasts to +1.8% and ~3.5% vs. the prior guidance of +2.3% and 4.0%.
Kohl’s (KSS) shares are falling in pre-market trading following a bottom-line miss in the company's latest quarterly earnings report.
For the quarter, Kohl’s reported EPS of $0.74, $0.12 below expectations on quarterly revenue that was flat year over year and was ahead of the consensus forecast.
For the quarter, Kohl's comparable sales of +0.4% missed the +0.8% consensus and gross margin of 36.3% came in below the expected 36.7%.
The company also revised its 2020 guidance lower to EPS of $4.75-$4.95 vs. its prior forecast of $5.15-$5.45 and the $5.19 consensus.
TJX Companies (TJX), the parent of TJ Maxx, Marshalls, HomeGoods, and HomeSense, is expected to report quarterly EPS of $0.66 on revenue of $10.3 billion.
Given this morning reports from Home Depot and Kohl’s we can safely say the company’s guidance will be closely scrutinized.

Shares of JinkoSolar (JKS) are moving higher in pre-market trading following quarterly results that showcased a 12.6% year over year jump in solar module shipments, leading to better than expected quarterly financials.
The company guided current quarter solar module shipments to a new quarter record, in the range of 4.2K-4.4K MW.
Apple (AAPL) has announced a press event titled “honoring our favorite apps and games of 2019” that will be held on December 2 at 4 PM ET.
Shutterstock (SSTK) announced the launch of an unlimited monthly subscription for Shutterstock Music.

The new plan is geared toward digital content creators, including YouTubers, podcast producers, and social media managers, offering a cost-efficient solution to licensing unlimited high-quality tracks at $149 per month.
FCC Chairman Ajit Pai announced his support Monday for a public auction to free up C-band spectrum, a key band currently used for delivering video content for next-generation 5G wireless networks.
Alibaba (BABA) announced that it will stop taking orders early, closing at 12 pm ET on Tuesday, for its $13.4 billion seconding listing in Hong Kong due to strong demand.
The final price that institutional investors will pay will be set by Wednesday evening Hong Kong time based on Tuesday’s closing price in New York.
The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey announced that a 13 MW solar project for the JFK International Airport has been awarded to SunPower (SPWR) and Goldman Sachs Renewable Power Group.
Sony Pictures Entertainment (SNE) bought out AT&T’s (T) stake in Game Show Network for around $500 million and now has 100% control of the company.
The network will continue to be carried on DirecTV.

• PagSeguro Digital (PAGS) is expected to deliver EPS of $1.20 on revenue of $1,498.9 million.
• Urban Outfitters (URBN) is expected to deliver EPS of $0.56 on revenue of $998.6 million.
